<subSubSection id="C355653DB25FFF8F997FF902FA7DF856" lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="519" pageId="7" pageNumber="518" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BF036B6B25FFF80997FF902FC5CF957" blockId="7.[813,1456,1747,2030]" box="[813,913,1747,1773]" pageId="7" pageNumber="518">REMARKS</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BF036B6B25FFF80997FF925FBD1F855" blockId="7.[813,1456,1747,2030]" pageId="7" pageNumber="518">
<bibRefCitation id="EFDE4B47B25FFF80997FF925FC33F8B5" author="GEIGER D. L." box="[813,1022,1780,1806]" pageId="7" pageNumber="518" refId="ref22775" refString="GEIGER D. L. 2012. - Monograph of the little slit shells Volume 1. Introduction, Scissurellidae, p. 1 - 728. Volume 2. Anatomidae, Larocheidae, Depressizonidae, Sutilizonidae, Temnocinclidae, p. 729 - 1291. Santa Barbara Museum of Natural History Monographs 7." type="journal volume" year="2012">Geiger (2012: 1108</bibRefCitation>
and distribution map) reported 
<taxonomicName id="4C4F4D35B25FFF809F03F925FBD4F895" authority="(Jeffreys, 1877)" baseAuthorityName="Jeffreys" baseAuthorityYear="1877" class="Gastropoda" family="Anatomidae" genus="Anatoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepetellida" pageId="7" pageNumber="518" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="tenuis">
<emphasis id="B93BEAA4B25FFF809F03F925FCA7F896" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="518">Anatoma tenuis</emphasis>
(Jeffreys, 1877)
</taxonomicName>
from three localities in the Canaries, ranging from 
<quantity id="4CB79B53B25FFF809991F8E2FB93F8F5" box="[963,1118,1843,1870]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.75" metricValueMax="9.0" metricValueMin="4.5" pageId="7" pageNumber="518" unit="m" value="675.0" valueMax="900.0" valueMin="450.0">450 to 900 m</quantity>
, without illustrating these lots. We found in our material three species of 
<taxonomicName id="4C4F4D35B25FFF809EB4F885FA88F8D5" authorityName="Woodward" authorityYear="1859" box="[1254,1349,1876,1902]" class="Gastropoda" family="Anatomidae" genus="Anatoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepetellida" pageId="7" pageNumber="518" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B93BEAA4B25FFF809EB4F885FA88F8D5" box="[1254,1349,1876,1902]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="518">Anatoma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, viz. 
<taxonomicName id="4C4F4D35B25FFF809F29F885FC65F836" baseAuthorityName="Philippi" baseAuthorityYear="1844" class="Gastropoda" family="Anatomidae" genus="Anatoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepetellida" pageId="7" pageNumber="518" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="aspera">
<emphasis id="B93BEAA4B25FFF809F29F885FC65F836" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="518">Anatoma aspera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4C4F4D35B25FFF8099EAF8A5FBD3F836" baseAuthorityName="Seguenza" baseAuthorityYear="1880" box="[952,1054,1908,1934]" class="Gastropoda" family="Anatomidae" genus="Anatoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepetellida" pageId="7" pageNumber="518" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="eximia">
<emphasis id="B93BEAA4B25FFF8099EAF8A5FBD3F836" box="[952,1054,1908,1934]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="518">A. eximia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and the species resembling 
<taxonomicName id="4C4F4D35B25FFF809F00F8A5FA7DF836" baseAuthorityName="Jeffreys" baseAuthorityYear="1877" box="[1362,1456,1908,1934]" class="Gastropoda" family="Anatomidae" genus="Anatoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepetellida" pageId="7" pageNumber="518" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="tenuis">
<emphasis id="B93BEAA4B25FFF809F00F8A5FA7DF836" box="[1362,1456,1908,1934]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="518">A. tenuis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
here illustrated (
<figureCitation id="13742A33B25FFF8099B1F842FBE9F816" box="[995,1060,1939,1965]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="8.[132,143,1167,1185]" captionTargetBox="[132,1455,216,1107]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[132,1455,216,1107]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIG. 3. — Anatoma richardi (Dautzenberg &amp; H. Fischer, 1896): A, B, shell from DW130 (3.7 mm diameter); C, scanning electron micrograph of another shell from the same locality (2.8 mm); D, protoconch and first teleoconch whorl of the same shell; E, protoconch and first teleoconch whorl of the lectotype of Scissurella tenuis Jeffreys, 1877 (USNM 181649,1). Scale bars: 100 µm. Small arrows: protoconch/teleoconch limit; large arrowheads: to the beginning of the selenizone (end of teleoconch I). (E, reproduced with the permission of the National Museum of Natural History, Smithsonian Institution, https://www.nmnh.si.edu/)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3726034" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3726034/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="518">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
A-D). Whereas for the first two we agree with 
<bibRefCitation id="EFDE4B47B25FFF8099FAF862FB9EF875" author="GEIGER D. L." box="[936,1107,1971,1998]" pageId="7" pageNumber="518" refId="ref22775" refString="GEIGER D. L. 2012. - Monograph of the little slit shells Volume 1. Introduction, Scissurellidae, p. 1 - 728. Volume 2. Anatomidae, Larocheidae, Depressizonidae, Sutilizonidae, Temnocinclidae, p. 729 - 1291. Santa Barbara Museum of Natural History Monographs 7." type="journal volume" year="2012">Geiger’s (2012)</bibRefCitation>
identifications, there are issues regarding the last one.
</paragraph>
<caption id="DF30663EB250FF8F9AD6FB5EFABEFB5E" ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3726034" ID-Zenodo-Dep="3726034" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3726034/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="519" startId="8.[132,143,1167,1185]" targetBox="[132,1455,216,1107]" targetPageId="8">
<paragraph id="8BF036B6B250FF8F9AD6FB5EFABEFB5E" blockId="8.[132,1455,1167,1253]" pageId="8" pageNumber="519">
FIG. 3. — 
<taxonomicName id="4C4F4D35B250FF8F9A86FB5EFDB1FB1A" authority="(Dautzenberg &amp; H. Fischer, 1896)" baseAuthorityName="Dautzenberg &amp; H. Fischer" baseAuthorityYear="1896" box="[212,636,1167,1185]" class="Gastropoda" family="Anatomidae" genus="Anatoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepetellida" pageId="8" pageNumber="519" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="richardi">
<emphasis id="B93BEAA4B250FF8F9A86FB5EFEAFFB1A" box="[212,354,1167,1185]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="519">Anatoma richardi</emphasis>
(Dautzenberg &amp; H. Fischer, 1896)
</taxonomicName>
: 
<emphasis id="B93BEAA4B250FF8F98D1FB5EFD5DFB1A" bold="true" box="[643,656,1167,1185]" pageId="8" pageNumber="519">A</emphasis>
, 
<emphasis id="B93BEAA4B250FF8F98C8FB5EFD6AFB1A" bold="true" box="[666,679,1167,1185]" pageId="8" pageNumber="519">B</emphasis>
, shell from DW130 (3.7 mm diameter); 
<emphasis id="B93BEAA4B250FF8F99BCFB5EFC31FB1A" bold="true" box="[1006,1020,1167,1185]" pageId="8" pageNumber="519">C</emphasis>
, scanning electron micrograph of another shell from the same locality (2.8 mm); 
<emphasis id="B93BEAA4B250FF8F9B38FB77FEB5FB03" bold="true" box="[362,376,1190,1208]" pageId="8" pageNumber="519">D</emphasis>
, protoconch and first teleoconch whorl of the same shell; 
<emphasis id="B93BEAA4B250FF8F990DFB77FCA6FB03" bold="true" box="[863,875,1190,1208]" pageId="8" pageNumber="519">E</emphasis>
, protoconch and first teleoconch whorl of the lectotype of 
<taxonomicName id="4C4F4D35B250FF8F9F05FB74FEFDFB75" authority="Jeffreys, 1877" authorityName="Jeffreys" authorityYear="1877" class="Gastropoda" family="Scissurellidae" genus="Scissurella" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepetellida" pageId="8" pageNumber="519" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="tenuis">
<emphasis id="B93BEAA4B250FF8F9F05FB74FF7BFB75" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="519">Scissurella tenuis</emphasis>
Jeffreys, 1877
</taxonomicName>
(USNM 181649,1). Scale bars: 100 µm. 
<emphasis id="B93BEAA4B250FF8F982EFB6DFD3CFB75" bold="true" box="[636,753,1212,1230]" pageId="8" pageNumber="519">Small arrows</emphasis>
: protoconch/teleoconch limit; 
<emphasis id="B93BEAA4B250FF8F99A1FB6DFB40FB75" bold="true" box="[1011,1165,1212,1230]" pageId="8" pageNumber="519">large arrowheads</emphasis>
: to the beginning of the selenizone (end of teleoconch 
<emphasis id="B93BEAA4B250FF8F9B77FB02FEE6FB5E" bold="true" box="[293,299,1235,1253]" pageId="8" pageNumber="519">I</emphasis>
). (E, reproduced with the permission of the National Museum of Natural History, Smithsonian Institution, https://www.nmnh.si.edu/).
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="8BF036B6B250FF8F9AC9FAE4FBD9FA34" blockId="8.[132,776,1333,2029]" lastBlockId="8.[813,1456,1333,2030]" pageId="8" pageNumber="519">
Our specimens have the suture of the last whorl either attached to the abapical keel of the selenizone, or dropping at some distance below this keel (leaving exposed a part of the previous whorl below the keel of the selenizone called “sutsel” by Geiger), with all transitional constructions. This questions the taxonomic value of this character, given by Geiger as a diagnostic of 
<taxonomicName id="4C4F4D35B250FF8F9B5CFA24FEABF9B5" authorityName="Jeffreys" authorityYear="1877" box="[270,358,1525,1551]" class="Gastropoda" family="Scissurellidae" genus="Scissurella" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepetellida" pageId="8" pageNumber="519" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="tenuis">
<emphasis id="B93BEAA4B250FF8F9B5CFA24FEABF9B5" box="[270,358,1525,1551]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="519">A. tenuis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
vs 
<taxonomicName id="4C4F4D35B250FF8F9BD6FA24FD1BF9B4" authority="(Seguenza, 1880)" baseAuthorityName="Seguenza" baseAuthorityYear="1880" box="[388,726,1525,1551]" class="Gastropoda" family="Anatomidae" genus="Anatoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepetellida" pageId="8" pageNumber="519" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="tenuisculpta">
<emphasis id="B93BEAA4B250FF8F9BD6FA24FDD4F9B4" box="[388,537,1525,1551]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="519">A. tenuisculpta</emphasis>
(Seguenza, 1880)
</taxonomicName>
. The latter species, originally described as a fossil from the Pliocene of southern Italy, is briefly compared to 
<taxonomicName id="4C4F4D35B250FF8F986BF9E4FD5BF9F5" authorityName="Jeffreys" authorityYear="1877" box="[569,662,1589,1615]" class="Gastropoda" family="Scissurellidae" genus="Scissurella" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepetellida" pageId="8" pageNumber="519" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="tenuis">
<emphasis id="B93BEAA4B250FF8F986BF9E4FD5BF9F5" box="[569,662,1589,1615]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="519">A. tenuis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by 
<bibRefCitation id="EFDE4B47B250FF8F98EDF9E5FEC2F9D5" author="GEIGER D. L." pageId="8" pageNumber="519" refId="ref22775" refString="GEIGER D. L. 2012. - Monograph of the little slit shells Volume 1. Introduction, Scissurellidae, p. 1 - 728. Volume 2. Anatomidae, Larocheidae, Depressizonidae, Sutilizonidae, Temnocinclidae, p. 729 - 1291. Santa Barbara Museum of Natural History Monographs 7." type="journal volume" year="2012">Geiger (2012: 1106</bibRefCitation>
, 1116), and stated to differ, in addition to the sutsel in having a “longer teleoconch I (0.75 vs 0.5 whorl)” and “a wider umbilicus”. Nonetheless in the description provided for 
<taxonomicName id="4C4F4D35B250FF8F9AFEF965FE87F975" baseAuthorityName="Seguenza" baseAuthorityYear="1880" box="[172,330,1716,1742]" class="Gastropoda" family="Anatomidae" genus="Anatoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepetellida" pageId="8" pageNumber="519" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="tenuisculpta">
<emphasis id="B93BEAA4B250FF8F9AFEF965FE87F975" box="[172,330,1716,1742]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="519">A. tenuisculpta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, teleoconch I is reported to be 0.5-0.85 whorl so that this difference from 
<taxonomicName id="4C4F4D35B250FF8F9BA2F905FD86F955" authorityName="Jeffreys" authorityYear="1877" box="[496,587,1748,1774]" class="Gastropoda" family="Scissurellidae" genus="Scissurella" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepetellida" pageId="8" pageNumber="519" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="tenuis">
<emphasis id="B93BEAA4B250FF8F9BA2F905FD86F955" box="[496,587,1748,1774]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="519">A. tenuis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is not diagnostic. Our own Canarian specimens have about‰.75 whorl of teleoconch I (
<figureCitation id="13742A33B250FF8F9AB5F8C5FEF6F895" box="[231,315,1812,1838]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="8.[132,143,1167,1185]" captionTargetBox="[132,1455,216,1107]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[132,1455,216,1107]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIG. 3. — Anatoma richardi (Dautzenberg &amp; H. Fischer, 1896): A, B, shell from DW130 (3.7 mm diameter); C, scanning electron micrograph of another shell from the same locality (2.8 mm); D, protoconch and first teleoconch whorl of the same shell; E, protoconch and first teleoconch whorl of the lectotype of Scissurella tenuis Jeffreys, 1877 (USNM 181649,1). Scale bars: 100 µm. Small arrows: protoconch/teleoconch limit; large arrowheads: to the beginning of the selenizone (end of teleoconch I). (E, reproduced with the permission of the National Museum of Natural History, Smithsonian Institution, https://www.nmnh.si.edu/)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3726034" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3726034/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="519">
Fig. 3 
<collectionCode id="ED5EAE73B250FF8F9B75F8C5FEF6F895" box="[295,315,1812,1838]" pageId="8" pageNumber="519">E</collectionCode>
</figureCitation>
). A further feature of the early teleoconch of both 
<taxonomicName id="4C4F4D35B250FF8F9A8EF8E5FEBAF8F6" baseAuthorityName="Seguenza" baseAuthorityYear="1880" box="[220,375,1843,1870]" class="Gastropoda" family="Anatomidae" genus="Anatoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepetellida" pageId="8" pageNumber="519" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="tenuisculpta">
<emphasis id="B93BEAA4B250FF8F9A8EF8E5FEBAF8F6" box="[220,375,1843,1870]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="519">A. tenuisculpta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as understood by 
<bibRefCitation id="EFDE4B47B250FF8F986CF8E2FD1AF8F5" author="GEIGER D. L." box="[574,727,1843,1870]" pageId="8" pageNumber="519" refId="ref22775" refString="GEIGER D. L. 2012. - Monograph of the little slit shells Volume 1. Introduction, Scissurellidae, p. 1 - 728. Volume 2. Anatomidae, Larocheidae, Depressizonidae, Sutilizonidae, Temnocinclidae, p. 729 - 1291. Santa Barbara Museum of Natural History Monographs 7." type="journal volume" year="2012">Geiger (2012)</bibRefCitation>
and our specimens, is the presence of a single spiral cord on the outer third of teleoconch I, abutting on the beginning of the selenizone (
<figureCitation id="13742A33B250FF8F9B78F842FE4CF816" box="[298,385,1939,1965]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="8.[132,143,1167,1185]" captionTargetBox="[132,1455,216,1107]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[132,1455,216,1107]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIG. 3. — Anatoma richardi (Dautzenberg &amp; H. Fischer, 1896): A, B, shell from DW130 (3.7 mm diameter); C, scanning electron micrograph of another shell from the same locality (2.8 mm); D, protoconch and first teleoconch whorl of the same shell; E, protoconch and first teleoconch whorl of the lectotype of Scissurella tenuis Jeffreys, 1877 (USNM 181649,1). Scale bars: 100 µm. Small arrows: protoconch/teleoconch limit; large arrowheads: to the beginning of the selenizone (end of teleoconch I). (E, reproduced with the permission of the National Museum of Natural History, Smithsonian Institution, https://www.nmnh.si.edu/)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3726034" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3726034/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="519">
Fig. 3 
<collectionCode id="ED5EAE73B250FF8F9B3BF842FE4CF816" box="[361,385,1939,1965]" pageId="8" pageNumber="519">D</collectionCode>
</figureCitation>
). This feature is found also on other species (e.g. 
<taxonomicName id="4C4F4D35B250FF8F9B59F862FEA4F876" baseAuthorityName="Philippi" baseAuthorityYear="1844" box="[267,361,1971,1997]" class="Gastropoda" family="Anatomidae" genus="Anatoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepetellida" pageId="8" pageNumber="519" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="aspera">
<emphasis id="B93BEAA4B250FF8F9B59F862FEA4F876" box="[267,361,1971,1997]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="519">A. aspera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) and is stable on all the specimens we examined, but the 
<typeStatus id="54F48814B250FF8F9B01F802FE78F856" box="[339,437,2003,2029]" pageId="8" pageNumber="519">lectotype</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName id="4C4F4D35B250FF8F9B88F802FD4AF856" authorityName="Jeffreys" authorityYear="1877" box="[474,647,2003,2029]" class="Gastropoda" family="Scissurellidae" genus="Scissurella" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepetellida" pageId="8" pageNumber="519" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="tenuis">
<emphasis id="B93BEAA4B250FF8F9B88F802FD4AF856" box="[474,647,2003,2029]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="519">Scissurella tenuis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
shows only strong, arched axial ribs fading before reaching the suture, no spiral cord (
<figureCitation id="13742A33B250FF8F999CFA84FBD3FAD4" box="[974,1054,1365,1391]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="8.[132,143,1167,1185]" captionTargetBox="[132,1455,216,1107]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[132,1455,216,1107]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIG. 3. — Anatoma richardi (Dautzenberg &amp; H. Fischer, 1896): A, B, shell from DW130 (3.7 mm diameter); C, scanning electron micrograph of another shell from the same locality (2.8 mm); D, protoconch and first teleoconch whorl of the same shell; E, protoconch and first teleoconch whorl of the lectotype of Scissurella tenuis Jeffreys, 1877 (USNM 181649,1). Scale bars: 100 µm. Small arrows: protoconch/teleoconch limit; large arrowheads: to the beginning of the selenizone (end of teleoconch I). (E, reproduced with the permission of the National Museum of Natural History, Smithsonian Institution, https://www.nmnh.si.edu/)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3726034" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3726034/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="519">
Fig. 3 
<collectionCode id="ED5EAE73B250FF8F9E59FA84FBD3FAD4" box="[1035,1054,1365,1391]" pageId="8" pageNumber="519">E</collectionCode>
</figureCitation>
) and the teleoconch 1 extends hardly more than 0.5 whorl.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BF036B6B250FF8F9911FA44FAFAF9D5" blockId="8.[813,1456,1333,2030]" pageId="8" pageNumber="519">
Our specimens are most likely conspecific with those reported by Geiger around the Canaries, Azores and Cape Verde Islands in the upper bathyal (
<quantity id="4CB79B53B250FF8F9E55FA04FB41FA54" box="[1031,1164,1493,1519]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.25" metricValueMax="13.4" metricValueMin="3.1" pageId="8" pageNumber="519" unit="m" value="825.0" valueMax="1340.0" valueMin="310.0">310-1340 m</quantity>
), and the same species is also known to us from Galicia Bank off the NW Iberian Peninsula, but these may not be correctly identified as 
<taxonomicName id="4C4F4D35B250FF8F9F54F9C4FA65F995" baseAuthorityName="Jeffreys" baseAuthorityYear="1877" box="[1286,1448,1557,1583]" class="Gastropoda" family="Anatomidae" genus="Anatoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepetellida" pageId="8" pageNumber="519" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="tenuis">
<emphasis id="B93BEAA4B250FF8F9F54F9C4FA65F995" box="[1286,1448,1557,1583]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="519">Anatoma tenuis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which has an abyssal 
<typeStatus id="54F48814B250FF8F9E5AF9E4FBFBF9F4" box="[1032,1078,1589,1615]" pageId="8" pageNumber="519">type</typeStatus>
locality south of Greenland and has a discrepant morphology of the early teleoconch.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BF036B6B250FF8F9911F9A5FA7DF856" blockId="8.[813,1456,1333,2030]" pageId="8" pageNumber="519">
The fossil 
<typeStatus id="54F48814B250FF8F99FFF9A4FBCFF934" box="[941,1026,1653,1679]" pageId="8" pageNumber="519">neotype</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName id="4C4F4D35B250FF8F9E71F9A4FB71F935" baseAuthorityName="Seguenza" baseAuthorityYear="1880" box="[1059,1212,1652,1679]" class="Gastropoda" family="Anatomidae" genus="Anatoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepetellida" pageId="8" pageNumber="519" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="tenuisculpta">
<emphasis id="B93BEAA4B250FF8F9E71F9A4FB71F935" box="[1059,1212,1652,1679]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="519">A. tenuisculpta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has the last whorl considerably narrower and dropping more distinctly down from the suture, than in any of the Recent specimens here discussed. The specimens from Norway illustrated by Geiger as 
<taxonomicName id="4C4F4D35B250FF8F9F1DF905FCA0F8B5" baseAuthorityName="Seguenza" baseAuthorityYear="1880" class="Gastropoda" family="Anatomidae" genus="Anatoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepetellida" pageId="8" pageNumber="519" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="tenuisculpta">
<emphasis id="B93BEAA4B250FF8F9F1DF905FCA0F8B5" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="519">A. tenuisculpta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have a much flatter spire and do not show essential difference with the Canarian specimens, apart from size and a somewhat less expanded last whorl. Conversely, 
<taxonomicName id="4C4F4D35B250FF8F9F1AF8E2FB31F8D6" authority="Dautzenberg &amp; H. Fischer, 1896" authorityName="Dautzenberg &amp; H. Fischer" authorityYear="1896" class="Gastropoda" family="Scissurellidae" genus="Scissurella" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepetellida" pageId="8" pageNumber="519" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="richardi">
<emphasis id="B93BEAA4B250FF8F9F1AF8E2FC4CF8D6" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="519">Scissurella richardi</emphasis>
Dautzenberg &amp; H. Fischer, 1896
</taxonomicName>
, described from 
<quantity id="4CB79B53B250FF8F997FF8A2FC73F835" box="[813,958,1907,1934]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.348" metricValueMax="1.396" metricValueMin="1.3" pageId="8" pageNumber="519" unit="m" value="1348.0" valueMax="1396.0" valueMin="1300.0">1300-1396 m</quantity>
off the Azores is certainly the same. For the time being, we find premature to assume the synonymy of 
<taxonomicName id="4C4F4D35B250FF8F9F00F845FCB2F876" baseAuthorityName="Dautzenberg &amp; H. Fischer" baseAuthorityYear="1896" class="Gastropoda" family="Anatomidae" genus="Anatoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepetellida" pageId="8" pageNumber="519" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="richardi">
<emphasis id="B93BEAA4B250FF8F9F00F845FCB2F876" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="519">Anatoma richardi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with either 
<taxonomicName id="4C4F4D35B250FF8F9E57F862FBACF876" baseAuthorityName="Jeffreys" baseAuthorityYear="1877" box="[1029,1121,1971,1997]" class="Gastropoda" family="Anatomidae" genus="Anatoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepetellida" pageId="8" pageNumber="519" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="tenuis">
<emphasis id="B93BEAA4B250FF8F9E57F862FBACF876" box="[1029,1121,1971,1997]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="519">A. tenuis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
or 
<taxonomicName id="4C4F4D35B250FF8F9EDAF862FAEEF876" baseAuthorityName="Seguenza" baseAuthorityYear="1880" box="[1160,1315,1971,1997]" class="Gastropoda" family="Anatomidae" genus="Anatoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepetellida" pageId="8" pageNumber="519" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="tenuisculpta">
<emphasis id="B93BEAA4B250FF8F9EDAF862FAEEF876" box="[1160,1315,1971,1997]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="519">A. tenuisculpta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and propose to use the former name for the Recent Macaronesian species.
</paragraph>
